referenced_message.content:
**For those of you wanting more info on how the launch randomness will work:**

1. When the smart contract is deployed, it makes a call to the Internet Computer Protocol to get true on-chain randomness. This is like a random seed.

2. Then there is a function on the smart contract to initialize a launch. This includes two steps, an airdrop and a sale.

3. When you call this function (ext_saleOpen) it uses the seed obtained from ICP in #1 and shuffles the tokens. This is as close to true randomness as you can get (because of the 32 bytes of randomness obtained from ICP). Then it allocates the first X tokens to the airdrop, which is still fully random because the token array was shuffled.

4. Further leveraging this shuffled token list, they are then made available for the sale, each purchase picking another off the randomly shuffled list. This token order is not available as a smart contract call (is only available as private data in the smart contract).

5. This model works (and is different from ETH launches) because (1) you can have private data on ICP and (2) you can get true randomness from ICP.

6. This is a fairly robust setup that I believe is sufficient for the Motoko Sentinels launch. There are ways that it can be improved in the future though.
